Condition code B means “Presentation of a certificate/licence/document” and is common to both conditions.
There is no trigger price (hence 4 * null fields across both conditions).
Action codes are complementary (27 and 7) – the 27 is the positive and the 7 is the negative.
The certificate required to effect the positive action is Y085

AND / OR logic for condition codes


Conditions are grouped together according to their condition code.
Within that group, the individual conditions are grouped together in an OR relationship, for example, in the conditions associated with the B condition code to the right, only one of the three noted goods needs to be provided, however it must be provided alongside one of the other conditions from block E being met (provision of a document or the weight of the imported good being below 2kg).
In this way, an additional tier is added to the logical condition model via the condition code grouping.



Volumes of conditions


Do not underestimate the complexity of measure conditions – there are up to 26 conditions on measures, as per the example here on commodity code 0308110000 (Aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, live, fresh, chilled, frozen, dried, salted or in brine; smoked aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, whether or not cooked before or during the smoking process; flours, meals and pellets of aquatic invertebrates other than crustaceans and molluscs, fit for human consumption)against the EU (measure_sid 3566626)
In this case, the conditions are aligned against 2 condition codes:


within condition code B and E respectively, any of the positive conditions will result in an acceptance of the trade.
at least one condition needs to be fulfilled within each of the two condition code groups.

The intellectual knowledge of certification is a huge challenge in DIT, Defra and HMG as a whole - over the implementation period, significant effort in DIT and Defra should be expended in looking to understand certification.


Detailed overview of condition codesCondition code A



This condition code is used to modify the circumstances of an anti-dumping or anti-subsidy duty depending on the conditions stated.
There are three scenarios in which this condition code is used, two of which have 2 related (and opposite action codes)


Scenario 1 – apply conditional duties depending on supply of document
Scenario 2 – determine if the trade can go ahead
Scenario 3 - determining applicability of exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty


Scenario 1 – apply conditional duties depending on supply of document


This is by far the most common application of conditional duties for trade remedy-related measures
The applicable duty can be conditional on the supply of a document: if the document is supplied then the duty is reduced
This scenario is executed by:


setting multiple (usually two) measure conditions with condition code A
then assigning action code 01, which states ”Apply the amount of the action”
and to each condition then assigning an applicable duty

The documents used in the EU, presumably to be followed in the UK are as follows:


D005 - Commercial invoice within the framework of undertakings
D008 - Invoice with a signed declaration
D017 - Commercial invoice within the framework of undertakings and Export Undertaking Certificate
D018 - Invoice for transactions which are not exempted from countervailing/anti-dumping duties


Scenario 2 – determine if the trade can go ahead at all


Features a pair of action codes which are always supplied together and are opposites of each other


08 - Declared subheading not allowed
The trade will be rejected in CDS
This is always associated with no document being specified, therefore not presented with the trade
28 - Declared subheading allowed
This is always associated with a document being specified, therefore presented with the trade and hence, the trade being permitted

There is only one certificate that has been used in conjunction with this condition code / action code permutation


D020 - Commercial invoice and mill certificate as defined in Regulation 2015/1953

This scenario is not currently in use, but it has been used in the past

Scenario 3 – determining applicability of exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty


As with scenario 2, this features a pair of conditions with complementing action codes that are always found together
Though not completely defunct, this is used only three times in current measures by the EU
The two action codes are:


34 - Apply exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty
14 - The exemption/reduction of the anti-dumping duty is not applicable

This basically means that the antidumping duty will be waived entirely or reduced according to the legislation. There are no conditional duties set however, therefore it is not 100% clear where the duty calculation will get its raw data from
The conditions should be applied in the sequence 34 then 14, i.e. positive followed by negative
There is only one current certificate in use that is used with this condition code / action code combination


D008 - Invoice with a signed declaration




Conditions B, C and H are identical in meaning
C and H are used when multiple condition sets using the same mechanic need to be applied to the same measure.

Condition codes B, C & H



Codes B, C and H require a certificate or other document to be presented in order for the requirement to be fulfilled.
Condition codes C & H are identical to condition code B, and there is no overt reason as to why C / H might be used instead of B – they are however sometimes used alongside code B.
Commodity code 8418690091 provides the answer as to why there are two types of condition that are ostensibly identical, i.e. there is a desire to apply multiple conditions sets to the same measure (in this case Import control of fluorinated greenhouse gases).
If just B had been used, it would not have been possible to apply the AND logic of the two condition groups.
H is used only 41 times (Jan 2020); C is used c. 5,000 times whereas B is vastly more prevalent (c. 24,000 occurrences).


Condition code E



This condition code is a combination of a quantitative restriction plus a documentation requirement, i.e. a trade will be allowed provided the volume of goods is lower than the defined threshold weight (or other unit), or a document is provided that permits the trade in a larger volume of goods.
The criteria that define these two conditions are set in the measure condition data.


Condition code I



These condition codes are currently used uniquely with measure types 751 and 755 (import and export control of waste)
They are functionally identical to condition code E (see above).
Type I is only ever used in conjunction with type E to present a send condition set of the same type, never on its own


Condition code F



These conditions allow duties to be charged against imported goods subject to Trade Remedies (Anti dumping or anti subsidy duties) that are dependent upon the unit price of the import.
This is significantly less commonly used than condition code A, which is also used to apply conditional logic to the trade of a good subject to an AD / AS duty, but remains an option for the TRA: there are 119 such conditions against 17,000 + of type A.
In the example to the right on measure 3571830 on commodity 2933610000 (melamine), there are two F-type conditions, which are dependent on the import price: the duties are set accordingly.
What these conditions say is:


if the goods is imported at a price of higher than €1153 per tonne, then apply zero additional punitive duty (condition 1)
BUT if the import of the good is at a lower price, apply the difference between the import price and the punitive duty

This essentially sets a minimum import 


Condition code L



This is currently used only 30 times and is always applied to measures of type 652 - Additional duty based on cif price
This measure type is used in managing a complex agricultural duty called “Representative prices for chicken”, which in the EU tariff is applied to certain poultry products that are being traded from Argentina, Brazil, Chile and Thailand – the most aggressive of chicken traders.
The UK is not going to be taking on this policy, unless plans change between now and the end of 2020.
The policy is far too complex to describe here, but is described in detail in the general training manual.

*Condition code M *



Condition code M is used in two circumstances:


The first circumstance is the in managing EU supplied credibility checks of type:
430 Control of particulars of the declaration (suspicious value/net weight or value/supplementary unit)
483 Declaration of subheading submitted to restrictions (value)

A credibility check is a mechanism that is employed in a border system to attempt to reduce errors in declarations by enforcing a check on (for example) the weight versus item count ratio of a declaration.
430 and 483 are measures (along with 431) that are used by the EU to ensure that discrepancies are avoided.
The EU provides these across the whole of the EU because they are trying to ensure consistency and reduce errors (that they have to fix for all 28 member states).
After EU Exit, the UK will provide its own credibility checks – the EU’s measures will be terminated
In reality, the EU’s credibility checks are a small subset of the overall number of checks that are carried out. CHIEF and CDS are replete with many UK-specific credibility checks as well. In the future, these will all be managed by HMRC, not by DIT MTPO, therefore are out of scope for DIT (albeit there is nothing to prevent TAP from creating these).
The second circumstance will continue after EU Exit, as it deals with Trade Remedies. The existing conditions of this type are against measure type ID 552 Definitive anti-dumping duty, but there is no reason why this would not also be assigned to measure types 551, 553 and 554.
This follows a similar pattern to other threshold-based commodities previously noted
There are currently (Jan 2020) 84 instances of condition code M.
In the examples to the right, there are two conditions which behave more or less the same as condition type F, where the applicable punitive duty is dependent the declared price [F depends on net free at frontier price before duty].


Condition code Q



Condition type Q is used in all cases where a measure is put in place to represent a licensed quota. And in all cases it refers to the single license Y100 (Special entries on the import licence AGRIM). It is used in measures of type:


122  Non preferential tariff quota
123  Non preferential tariff quota under end-use
142  Tariff preference
143  Preferential tariff quota

It is only used for licensed quotas; it is never used for FCFS quotas.


Condition code R



As per scenario 1 for condition code M, this is used to apply conditions to credibility checks to ensure that the weight ‘looks right’ against the number of declared goods. The supplementary unit identifies what additional unit beyond the KGM weight must be supplied by the trader on declaring their import.
Again, as per condition code M, the UK will be abandoning the practise of managing credibility checks in the Taric file after EU Exit.

Condition code U



As per scenario 1 for condition codes M & R, this is used to apply conditions to credibility checks to ensure that the declared value ‘looks right’ against the number of declared goods.
The supplementary unit identifies what additional unit beyond the KGM weight must be supplied by the trader on declaring their import.
As per condition codes M & R, the UK will be abandoning the practise of managing credibility checks in the Taric file after EU Exit.

Condition code V – The Entry price System


The Entry Price System (EPS) is a complex mechanism to apply tiered duties to 31 agricultural products, primarily fruit.
The EPS is described in detail elsewhere, so this page will not go into that much detail, especially as the UK will be abandoning the Entry Price System. It supports growers of (primarily) citrus fruits in Southern Europe: the UK’s less sunny climes do not lend themselves to industrial-scale citriculture.




The screen above is captured from the third country duty for cherry tomatoes – this shows the EPS in action.
The duties that are applicable depend on the import price: the cheaper the import, the more expensive the duty
The purpose of this is to protect domestic growers in s. Europe from influxes of very cheap goods

Condition code V

The data for EPS-related measures is as per the example to the right – just one row (marquee below).

In the example above, each row is a price threshold: if the import price falls below a given threshold, then the duty from the row below is charged.

This is, as its name suggests a catch all that can be used to manage effectively any condition not specifically covered by the other condition codes. In practice, this seems to have been used in the past by the EU for managing certificates, much in the vein of conditions with code B, C or H. But the real reason for using this is for non-specific conditions that are not associated with a specific document.
These miscellaneous conditions are linked to in much the same way that certificates are referenced, using the certificate type code and certificate code fields. Here are a few examples of conditions that are referenced by condition code Y. None of these are documents per se: they reference properties of goods or activities undertaken by traders outside of the core declaration flow.
For example:
* Y019  Request for preferential treatment for Iceland
* Y021  Request for EEA preferential treatment
* Y034  Derogation from export prohibition by virtue of Article 4.1 of Council Regulation (EU) 2017/1509
* Y037  Goods exempted from the prohibition – biathlon equipment
None of the conditions linked to via the condition code ‘Y’ utilise the price threshold fields.
Condition code Z

Condition code Z is used solely on national P & R measures currently, though it is by no means a stipulation that this has to be so. Indeed, all the national P & R will become homogenised with the measures inherited from the EU after EU Exit – though the management of measures to support the NI Protocol may influence the specific approach.
These are the measure types where Z is used:


ATT   Attestation Document (horticulture and potatoes)
CEX   DCMS Open General Export Licence
COE   Home Office Controlled Drugs (export)
COI   HMI Conformity Certificate (fruit and veg) issued in UK
EQC   Certificate of Conformity
HOP   Home Office pre-cursor chemical authorisation
PRE   Home Office Pre-cursor chemicals
PRT   Home Office Controlled Drugs (import)

There is no reason why this condition code should be used in preference to B, C or H. Indeed there are occasions where the Z type is used, but only one positive condition is included, which seems to make the condition type pretty redundant (e.g. with EQC measures).
The advice to tariff managers would be to always use condition code B, then C then H before resorting to Z.
Key business processing rules
        
          
#
Rule
Notes


ME53
The referenced measure condition must exist.
Required   This applies when assigning conditions components to   conditions A measure obvs has to be in existence too for a measure condition   to be generated in the first place.


ME54
The validity period of the referenced measure condition   must span the validity period of the measure.
Not required - disregard   As far as we can see, this is an erroneous business rule:   the measure condition table does not have a start and end date field. The   condition adopts the start and end dates of the parent measure. Similarly,   there are no start and end dates associated with a measure condition   component (or for that matter a measure component). They all adopt the date   constraints of the parent measure.


ME55
A measure condition refers to a measure condition or to a condition   + certificate or to a condition + amount specifications.
Disregard   This has been written so vaguely that there are no rules   to be gleaned from it

The referenced certificate must exist.
Required   A certificate must exist before being assigned to a   condition – match must be made on the 2 clustered primary key fields of   certificate type code and certificate code

The validity period of the referenced certificate must   span the validity period of the measure.
Required   The optimal way for us to handle this is to NEVER expire   certificates – there is literally no need. However the validity start dates   and end dates of the measure and the certificate need to be checked. See note   at the foot of this document as to how null end dates have been dealt with in   terms of comparing extents – to reduce code

Required    Conditions are put in place to respond either to the   provision of some sort of document / license or to respond to a minimum   threshold import price – if the latter then there is a requirement to specify   a valid monetary unit, which is always likely to be GBP.

Measurements have start and end dates against them, and these also   need to be observed.

The validity period of the measurement unit must span the   validity period of the measure.
Required   Measurement units have start dates end dates – we need   to observe these start and end dates in the creation of measures. We are not   offering a tool to manage measurement units in the first instance.

Required   Measurement unit qualifiers have start dates end dates   – we need to observe these start and end dates in the creation of measures.   We are not offering a tool to manage qualifiers in the first instance.

18.content:
Quotas


Quotas




Introduction to quotas


First Come, First Served Quotas


In-depth view of data tables


Licensed quotas


Quota user needs


Quota business rules






Introduction to quotas

A quota is used as a means of controlling the flow of goods into a country in order to create a balance between:


the needs of consumers or manufacturing industries that would use the item as a component or ingredient in producing something else in the importing countries and
domestic producers of the good, whose livelihood depends on producing and selling a product to domestic customers at full market price.

For example, tomatoes are imported into the European Union from Mediterranean countries and other places with temperate climates in order to satiate the needs of European citizens for tomatoes and sauces containing tomatoes. In Southern Europe, there are tomato growers for whom the overseas suppliers are rivals that threaten their livelihood.
In the UK, sheep farmers depend on selling their goods to a UK market hungry for lamb and lamb products; but there is not enough lamb in the UK to satisfy our needs, hence the need to import lamb from New Zealand and other countries.
This is a fine balance that needs to be managed carefully in order to support the needs of the two contrasting needs: the need for the nation to consume and need for domestic suppliers to make a living.
This is where quotas come in.


Get to know Peter Ungphakorn


Peter Ungphakorn was a senior information officer with the WTO Secretariat until 2015.
Since then he has moved into journalism, focusing mainly on international trade rules, agreements and institutions and fortunately making his knowledge available to the public via his Trade Beta Blog.
This blog contains very good, simple explainers (for seven and a half year-olds) on a number of topics, including quotas.




Read above about Tariff Rate Quotas (TRQs) (less so quantitative restrictions)
See also his blog on Meursing tables which simplifies an incredibly complex subject.

What is a quota?


A quota allows a certain volume of goods to be imported into a country at a reduced duty rate.
Once that volume has been imported, then the quota is considered to be exhausted and is no longer available to draw down against.
At that point, all importers will be forced to import the goods at the full (or less preferential duty rate).


What properties does a quota have?


Returning to the lamb quota on the previous screen, clicking on the term “092016” shows more detail of the quota.
“092016” is the quota order number. If any trader wants to take advantage of the preferential duties associated with a quota, then they need to quote that 6-digit quota order number on their import declaration. A quota1 has properties such as those shown here
These properties are described on the following pages


Defining quotas
There are multiple ways of defining and grouping quotas, all of which will be relevant to the delivery of the next iteration of the Tariff Application:


Administration mechanism:


First come first served 
Licensed

Legislative mechanism:


WTO quota
ATQ
preferential quota as part of an FTA 
safeguard quota

Origin quota: 


Yes
No


If you were to draw a Venn-style diagram of how these slices fit together, it would look a bit like this:

Preferential vs Non-Preferential quotas
Preferential quotas


The term preferential means that a single country or bloc is afforded treatment that provides better market access / lower duties than other countries.
In practical terms, preferential tariff duties and quotas are almost always made available via (Free) Trade Agreements. The quota is agreed as part of the bilateral negotiation between the two parties that provides each with mutual benefits.
Preferential quotas are always applied at a specific country or small group of countries.
Within the EU, there are a very small number of quotas which are applied to multiple countries (e.g. a wine quota available for imports from multiple W. Balkan countries), but most are aimed explicitly at one country or bloc.
Among the few exceptions, Greenland benefits from preferential quotas on seafoods outside of a formal Trade Agreement

Non-Preferential quotas


Non-preferential quotas are aimed at maintaining the balance of trade flows on critical goods by opening up a specific volume of market access to all overseas nations – in most cases, the non-preferential quotas are assigned to ERGA OMNES1 (the country group that includes all countries).
There are very few officially non-preferential quotas that have been opened up to specific countries only, where there is a need to maintain global trade flows with a less blunt instrument than a global non-preferential quota applied to the entire world, especially where there are trade titans in a particular commodity
Lamb is again a great example of this – there is a non-preferential quota for Erga Omnes (small volume) and much larger non-prefs for specific countries like Chile, Australia and New Zealand – each of which is a dominant player in the lamb trade.

Ways of administering quotas
There are two methods of administering a quota:
First Come First Served quotas


These are by far the most common of the two types of quota.
As the name suggests, a FCFS quota involves making a pot available to traders: whoever claims against that pot first gets to take advantage of the reduced rate.
If you’re not quick enough, you miss the opportunity and pay the non-preferential rate.

Licensed quotas


The purpose of a licensed quota is the same as a FCFS quota: to protect the fine balance of trade flows, however the mechanism for applying for usage is very different.
For each quota, periods of the year are opened up for importers to apply for licenses from the Rural Payments Agency (RPA) - a division of Defra.
During this period, the RPA accepts these license requests and issues licenses according to the specific rules of the quota
In the EU tariff, all licensed quotas’ 6-digit quota order numbers begin with “094”.

Origin quotas
Some quotas identify as Origin Quotas (about 25%)
Origin quotas allow for specific quantities of some products to receive preferential tariff treatment if the products meet certain conditions, for example a proof of origin can be provided to prove that the goods do in fact come from the specific country.
Origin quotas are always preferential in nature.
For a good example of an origin quota, please see the cat & dog food quota in place with Canada, where a proof of origin certificate is explicitly required.

The reason why this is important is that a quota’s origin status is displayed on the reference documents that accompany a trade agreements (as a schedule to the primary SI).
WTO quotas


The UK declares a tariff “schedule of concessions” to the WTO which is made up of multiple elements – what interests us most here is:
the tariff schedule
the schedules for tariff quotas on agricultural and non-agricultural products
The quota schedules list the concessions that we will make to overseas nations to provide greater market access to our market than would have been afforded by adopting the MFN rate alone.
In most cases, WTO quotas are assigned to the whole world (ERGA OMNES), but in certain cases (e.g. with lamb), the quota concessions are made available to individual countries which major in a certain trade (e.g. New Zealand for lamb).
Almost all WTO quotas are agricultural goods (this also applies to the other kinds of quota).


Autonomous quotas (ATQs)


Autonomous quotas are represented in the tariff as simple “Non-preferential quotas”. These are particularly applicable within the fishing industry. There is contention within the fishing industry between the catching sector and the food and processing sector.
For highly consumed goods, such as cod, pollock and prawns, the UK / EU catching industry cannot catch sufficient product to satisfy the needs of the home and international market. Therefore the processing industry needs access to low or zero duty for such products, while the catching industry needs protection by retaining at least some maximum import threshold above which normal tariff duties apply.
The autonomous tariff rate quota (ATQ) facilitates this compromise – a quantity of goods can be imported into the EU at zero or low rate, until exhausted, at which point the duty reverts to the third country rate
ATQs are set on a three year cycle: the ATQ duty rate cannot be changed in the course of that 3 year cycle, however the starting balance for each year can be assessed at the start of each year.
For fisheries ATQs, there is an additional point of interest, that, if 80% or more of the quota has been exhausted by the end of September in any given year, then the balance of the quota is increased by 20%
Autonomous Quotas so called, as the EU unilaterally decides to open a quota – there is no requirement for recourse to WTO approval to open an ATQ.
It is anticipated that the ATQs will continue to operate post-Brexit as they are favoured within the Defra ministry and offer a compromise to the different parts of the industry.

What products are covered by quotas?

Identifying quota types


Unfortunately, it is not a simple matter to take a quota order number and determine what kind of quota is being used. In the EU Tariff:


All current EU quota order numbers begin with 09 without exception
“094” means licensed quota
Autonomous agriculture quotas begin 0977
Autonomous fisheries quotas begin 0987

Apart from that, there are few obvious rules that define the EU’s use of quotas.
The system for identifying quotas in the UK tariff will be determined in the course of 2020.

Managing quota order numbers


DIT must take the lead in managing quota order numbers – this process has been introduced but not properly observed.
It needs to be a consultative process between DIT, HMRC and Defra to avoid errors and confusion, e.g. reusing existing quota order numbers
How quotas get set up is dependent on what they have been used for previously – we have inadvertently selected quota order numbers that were a cross section of closed and open quota order numbers, which have caused management challenges in previous migrations.
As of March 26th, the likelihood is that quota order numbers in the UK will be using ”08” as their first two digits to differentiate from the EU, with specific challenges around the dual Tariff in Northern Ireland being the primary cause. This remains to be agreed and properly analysed however.

Quotas in reference documents



To the left is a sample of the quota section of a reference document – it lists the quotas that are applicable to a given country or trading bloc (here is a mocked-up reference document for the ESA1 trading bloc).
The three highlighted data elements (with largely made up data for illustration purposes only), are data fields over and above what the Taric requires: these are not data that is needed by the HMRC systems, but is of benefit to creating reference documents.
In TAPv1, the reference document creation service had been created as a totally separate application (using Python / Django), whereas in round 2, it needs to be integrated.
Please see the training document on reference documents for more information

First Come, First Served Quotas

First Come, First Served quotas are far more prevalent than licensed quotas on the Tariff database.
As the name suggests this favours those traders that apply for the quota first
Then, once the initial volume assigned to the quota has been fully depleted, the quota is deemed to be exhausted and is no longer available to draw down against. Once depleted, the trader’s import then falls back on the next best import duty, which may be a tariff preference, but it more likely just the MFN duty.
There is an important difference in the way in which FCFS are managed compared to licensed quotas:
FCFS quotas pass through the HMRC systems that are of greatest interest to the DIT Tariff Application (CHIEF and CDS)
Licensed quotas do not touch HMRC systems: instead they are handled essentially off-system via the RPA (see following slides)
The way in which the DIT application handles the different types of quotas is very different, as will be discussed.

First Come First Served (FCFS) quotas: in the EU and with CHIEF
This diagram shows the data flows of traders making declarations on CHIEF against the EU’s quota allocation system for first come, first served quotas. At the time of writing (March 2020), 100% of the UK’s FCFS quota-related trade goes via this route (i.e. no involvement from CDS).

First Come First Served (FCFS) quotas: in the EU still and with CDS
The migration of CHIEF to CDS had been planned some time before the referendum, as CHIEF is legacy software that, despite being highly reliable, is difficult to maintain and extend to cater for new requirements (such as full adherence to the UCC -  Union Customs Code). This diagram is an extension of the previous diagram while CHIEF is excluded from this diagram (to save complexity), it will still be in place for some time anyway – and thanks to the NI Protocol, probably for another 2 years at least. In reality, this planned architecture will not be available to GB traders for the foreseeable future, thanks to the required pivot to support NI.

NI Protocol has changed the approach to CDS migration and this impacts quotas
The NI Protocol requires (over-simplified):


all goods imported into Northern Ireland to be subject to EU regulatory controls in full
all goods considered to be at risk of entering the EU via the NI / ROI boundary to be subject to EU import duties
while those goods that are not at risk are subject to GB duties

This requires 2 tariffs to be present to work out the applicable duties based on the circumstances of the individual trade. This is too complex to do in CHIEF and a huge overhead to do in two systems concurrently anyway.
Therefore CDS is now designated solely for NI traders (plus the 10 traders that have already been migrated), whereas all other (GB) traders will remain on CHIEF until a future date (to be specified).
The impact on quotas is that, by extension, imports to NI of at risk goods may still claim on EU quotas, and these requests will continue to need to be allocated via the EU Quota 2 system while UK quotas will be allocated by the new CDS Quota Allocation Module (QAM). There is a strong possibility for confusion for traders if the UK continues to share the same quota order numbers as the EU.
Architecture to support NI post Transition Period
Key points to note in this diagram – CDS will have two tariff modules, one served by the EU to support NI regulatory controls and at risk duties, the other to support GB trade and NI not at risk trade. In theory (to be negotiated and unlikely to be deliverable by Jan 21), NI at risk goods will be able to take advantage of EU quotas, and therefore be allocated via Quota 2, not QAM. CHIEF GB declarations will send quota requests to QAM for allocation.

The Taric and FCFS quotas
The data objects that are utilised for FCFS are vastly more numerous than those used for licensed quotas
Licensed quotas essentially use just measures not any of the other quota related tables. That is because all the other tables are set up uniquely to manage the set up and decrementing of quota balances.

The timespans of a FCFS quota


There are no limits on the periods that quotas can span, but there are commonalities, which these pages aim to share.
There are no quotas that are essentially one-offs – a quota is a permanent instrument to balance trade, not a one-time hit. The only slight deviation from this concerns the quotas that have been put in place to provide checks and balances on the import of steel goods (Steel safeguards), which evolve annually: this is just because the instrument is immature, not because it is a one-off.
The following types of quota periodicity can be found in the tariff:


Annual full year quota running from Jan 1st to December 31st and repeating every year
Annual full year quota running from another start date (e.g. July 1st to June 30th) and repeating every year
Part year quota running from any date to any other date (e.g. Feb 14th to May 31st) and repeating between the same dates every year
Quarterly quota running from Jan 1st to December 31st and repeating on that pattern every year
Quarterly quota running from another start date but lasting a full 12 months and repeating on that pattern every year
Part year quota split into monthly sections and repeating every year

These periods are enshrined in the legislation that engenders them – there is no deviation on the start and end dates of the periods (though watch out for leap years)

Timespans in graphical format

Impact of European growing seasons

There are more factors at play in determining quota volumes and periods than growing seasons (or marketing periods as they are called), but time of year is important for the EU, especially for Mediterranean countries.
In time, seasonality may be of less importance to the UK, as our climate does not (yet) suit the industrial levels of production seen in Southern Europe.
Quota staging


The ultimate goal of a trade agreement is often to get to a place where there is a 0% import duty on goods being imported
But, if that goal were to be reached immediately, the toxic shock to domestic producers would be potentially crippling, as  internal markets are swept away in one fell swoop by cheap and abundant imports.
Therefore the idea of staging has been adopted to allow domestic businesses to adjust to the new reality over time.
Staging periods equate to the period over which a trade agreement reaches it ultimate goal:


for tariff preferences, this is usually finite. For example, an agreement may include the goal to reduce an import duty from 10% (the pre-agreement MFN) to 0% over 4 years, reducing by 2.5% per year. After 4 years, the duty remains at 0% for as long as the agreement remains in place
for staging in quotas, there is no finite end goal, just an increase in the volume of goods made available to the quota. For example at the start of a trade agreement, a quota may permit the import of 100,000 KGM of goods at a reduced rate. The agreement states that an additional 10,000 KGM are permitted per year. I have not seen a ceiling placed on this (e.g. an extra 10,000 KGM a year until it reached 200,000 KGM), but that does not mean it does not happen. The relaxation always takes place against the quota volume, not against the in-quota duties.

Staging often appears in quotas created as part of a Trade Agreement, but never in WTO quotas or ATQs

Safeguard quotas


Since 2018, the EU has imposed quotas as part of its Steel Safeguards programme. Since 2017, USA has imposed swingeing import duties on steel and related goods coming into the country in order to protect its own industry from collapse
This led to a huge increase in the quantities of such goods coming into the European Union, as manufacturers (usually in the Far East), who previously had easy pickings in USA, now had to seek alternative markets.
The knock-on impact was felt in EU domestic steel suppliers, hence the imposition of steel safeguards by the EU.
Safeguards had been extremely rare in the EU until 2018 and the use of quotas to support them had never been seen. Now they are part of the EU’s defence armoury and will be adopted largely like-for-like by the UK after the end of the implementation period.
The safeguard works like this:


a punitive duty of 25% import duty (type 696 – Additional duties (safeguard)) is applied to multiple steel products grouped in 28 categories. The duty is applied to c. 100 countries
then individual quotas are overlaid to remove the duties for certain countries up to a given volume – different quotas are set up for each of the 28 groups (with many country exclusions), some of the quotas being annual and some of the quotas being quarterly

This function is documented in detail elsewhere – warning: it is hugely complex and warrants very detailed attention.
Knowing about the concepts behind quotas before digging into the safeguards will prepare you for the complexity.

Introductory periods


There are very many cases where an annual cadence is set up for a quota with an introductory period at the start that allows the quota to, for example, coincide with the Day One live implementation of a trade agreement, but to still allow the cadence to follow a marketing period.
This ‘introductory period’ will be critical also in the migration of quotas from the EU to the UK – if the implementation period ends on December 31st 2020, then there will be many quotas which will naturally start in the UK tariff on 1st January 2021, 


This is the mode (annual quotas that run for a calendar year).
But, any quota that does not commence on Jan 1st for its annual cadence will potentially require an introductory period
for example, an annual quota that starts on July 1st will require a 6-month introductory period
the steel safeguard quotas that typically run in quarters from July 1st to June 30th will require two introductory periods of three months each
but a quotas which runs from Valentine’s day to the end of June will not

      Criticality


As described above, the critical state determines if a trader needs to pay securities when utilising the quota.
The purpose of the requirement to collect securities is to


a) attempt to provide some sort of level playing field for traders as a quota reaches exhaustion
b) try to reduce returns towards the end of a definition’s active life span – managing returns is a hassle and if a trader has paid a security, the are less likely to be blasé with unused quota volume.

It is up to DIT to set the critical state of a quota definition, as we set all the properties of a quota definition period before it has begun, including critical state.
The rules of thumb are:
a new quota should be set to critical for three years so that there is an opportunity to study trade flows to determine if the volumes are correct
setting critical to ‘Y’ for this period ensures that the trade flow is more reflective of actual trade, dispensing with traders that declare a need for quota volume, but then do not use it.
BUT at the same time, for HMRC to take securities is a major overhead and they prefer not to in all cases.
So, during the 3 non-Brexits to date, the critical state for all quota definition periods has been set to N initially:


in order to reduce workload for HMRC
because most trade flows were fairly well known through UK;s membership of the EU
we were not introducing many genuinely new quotas (though the maxim was applied to all)

HMRC will need to be consulted in the lead-up to the implementation period on what they want to do with criticality: it is their domain, but our responsibility to set the initial state. This will be especially vital if we kick off any brand new trade deals with new overseas trading partners on Day One, which is remotely possible.

Managing geography

A FCFS quota only works when the full set of quota tables and measure tables are all set up and synchronised. It’s important to understand a few points around the geography of these two entities in order to create the right data.
* geography has to be set correctly against both the measure and the quota order number
* while the measures table has a 1-2-1 relationship with geographical areas, the quota order number table can relate to multiple origins via the many-to-many linking table “quota order number origins”.
*Geographical areas – concepts *
Assigning quotas to countries


A quota can be assigned either to an individual country or to a group of countries
As described on the previous page, it may also be assigned to multiple (single) countries as well; theoretically, there is no reason why the quota cannot be assigned to multiple country groups simultaneously, though this has never happened.
There are currently (in the EU tariff) several quotas that are assigned to multiple (single) countries, but these will not carry over into the UK tariff (needs to be re-checked).


For example, quota order number 091530 is assigned to import of wines from the Western Balkan states of Albania, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Kosovo, North Macedonia, Montenegro and Serbia.
While the UK will aim to engineer trade agreements with all 6 of these prior to the end of the implementation period, the quotas will be split into individual quotas per country.

The aim must be to still permit assignment of quotas to multiple countries however, as the model permits it.
For each assignment of geographical area to quota order number, the following is required:


a record in the measures table, linking geographical_area_id and ordernumber.
a record in the quota_order_number_origins table, linking geographical_area_id and quota_order_number_id.


Excluding countries from quotas


When a quota is assigned to a country group, it is possible and very common to exclude countries from that group, such that the quota does not apply to that country. Examples of this are:


quotas that apply on food and drink that apply to Central America, but from which Panama is excluded
almost all of the steel safeguard quotas feature multiple exclusions.

Obviously, the excluded country may be a member of the country group that’s assigned to the quota.
For each exclusion of a country from a quota associated to a country group, the following is required:


a record in the quota order number origin exclusions table, linking the origin and the excluded geographical area.
a record in the measure_excluded_geographical_areas table, linking the origin and the excluded geographical area.

Quota order number origins have start dates and end dates
Quota order number origins do not have start dates and end dates
If you want to alter the quota order number origin exclusions for a quota, and you don’t want it to happen immediately, you cannot just add the exclusion to the origin: it will take effect immediately, which is almost certainly not the requirement.
As case in point is the steel safeguards:


each year to date, the origin exclusions have been tweaked as the EU has discovered more about world trade flows and the impact of both the US and EU safeguards on that flow
the EU has not been able to just remove and add exclusions

There are two options:


either end the origin and start another origin
or end the quota order number and start another quota order number with a new origin

The EU chooses the latter option: terminating the quota order number and replacing with another one starting the next day with a new origin.


in TAP1, we followed this route: the alternative route may also be followed.

      Licensed quota process – by example (garlic)


Possible garlic traders are grouped into two groups:

Introduction to additional codesWhat is an additional code?


As detailed in the training manual on goods nomenclature (commodity codes), in most cases, the 10 digits of the EU commodity code hierarchy are fully sufficient to identify the product that is being traded.
However, there are certain scenarios where the 10-digits are not enough and an additional 4 digits are required (and sometimes 8) to communicate sufficient information to describe the trade.
This is where additional codes come in.




Additional codes may be appended to a commodity code to make the number of (effective) digits up to 14, or possibly 18.
Importantly though, there is no such thing as a 14-digit commodity code: commodity codes can be augmented by additional codes, but the two entities are managed completely separately: a single additional code can and usually is appended to multiple commodity codes through the medium of measures; similarly a single commodity code can have an association with multiple additional codes, again through measures applied to a given combination of commodity and additional code.

What are additional codes used for?


Additional codes are now used to manage:


Meursing codes – for sugar, flour and milk duties associated with complex agricultural products
Anti-dumping & anti-subsidy duties – to identify the specific company to which a punitive measure is attached
Pharma products – to identify that the end use of an imported good is for pharmaceutical purposes, and therefore attracts a reduced duty
Differentiating product states / uses / origins (e.g. waste chemicals, underwear [!])
Route of ingress – to identify the route goods (wheat & other cereals) take into EU and to apply different tariff or regulatory treatment
Works of art – to identify items stolen from Syria and Iraq as a result of wartime activity

Each of the above uses are discussed in detail on the following slides.
Additional codes are made up of 4 digits, which are split into two parts:


Structure of additional codes and additional code types


Much like certificates and footnotes, additional codes are made up of a type and then a specific ID, which, when concatenated, form the unique ID of the additional code. .
For example, the additional code C233 is constructed of a type © and a specific footnote ID (233) – the entire additional code is known as C233.
The numeric IDs, running from 001 to 999 can be reused across multiple additional code type IDs.
While the schema allows for us to use alphanumeric digits for additional codes, not just numeric, these are almost never used and never by the EU – there are 7 national additional codes that are used by HMRC for VAT and excise.
The use of the alphanumeric codes may be of great importance to the Northern Ireland protocol, subject to the way in which the solution progresses.
Additional code type IDs are always single alphabetical characters (those set by the EU) or single numeric characters (set as national additional code by the UK).

These   additional codes are used to differentiate between specific states of certain   chemical compounds: if the product is in a certain state, then a different   export code restriction applies, as explained in the footnote:          “The   surveillance does not apply to mixtures and natural products which contain   scheduled substances and which are compounded in such a way that the   scheduled substances cannot be easily used or extracted by readily applicable   or economically viable means, to medicinal products as defined in point 2 of   Article 1 of Directive 2001/83/EC of the European Parliament and of the   Council and to veterinary medicinal products as defined in point 2 of Article   1 of Directive 2001/82/EC of the European Parliament and of the Council.”          The   purpose of the these codes is to provide the ability to slice multiple   commodities according to their intrinsic properties.

I   kid you not – this group of additional codes is to apply additional   restrictions to the import of pants and bras from North Korea. The additional   code provides an additional slide over the top of the existing commodities   without creating multiple new comm codes.


        
      Type 4 – Restriction codesThink of this type of additional codes as a means of differentiating between:
potential multiple uses of goods, where splitting all the codes would be inadvisable, complex, confusing, or impossible
a way of differentiating origin / specifics, even if via several intermediary steps

        
          
Code(s)
Description & notes


4   008 – 4 099
These   codes have been instituted as a means of instituting temporary controls   (restrictions) on goods that have been plundered following the chaos in Iraq   and Syria, for example after the destruction of Palmyra. Rather than   permanently splitting existing commodity codes, typically (but not   exclusively) in chapters 97 and 98 (works of art) etc., the European   Commission has created additional codes to determine origin of goods, even if   they have passed through multiple trades prior to the entry into the EU. For   this reason, many of the controls apply not just to Iraq and Syria, but also   to Erga Omnes / All third countries (1011, 1008 respectively).          Chapters   97 and 98 are very shallow – in some cases, the definitions only go down to   HS4 without any further cleaving of codes – the EU cannot introduce codes at   6 digits, even if that was desirable, so the choice would have been: create a   very few additional codes to designate source OR create a large number of   10-digit codes to represent permanent splits.


4   115 to 4 118
Used   to apply controls to waste materials and ozone-depleting substances


4   200 to 4 212
Used   to differentiate the skins and furs of wild cats (e.g. lynxes) as well as   other mammals sometimes (illegally) used for their fur (e.g. otters &   pine martens)


        
      Type 7 - Meursing codes

Introduced in 1988 by the European Commission. Traders hate them, but we have to keep Meursing classifications or change our WTO commitments.
They apply to bakery and confectionery products, etc. classed as “composite agrigoods”. Meursing allows extra set of import duties to be charged depending on how much of 4 agricultural ingredients are used to make the product: milk fat, milk proteins, starch or glucose, or various forms of sugar.
The result used to be tens of thousands of categories of composite agrigoods for the purposes of charging import duties. To find the specific ‘recipe’ and the duties applicable, you look it up in the Meursing table (right).
Executed in the tariff as a combination of primary measures, such as tariff preferences, with complex duty expression combinations, which are then expanded when the trader select the ‘additional code’ for the specific ‘recipe’ of their product.
The best description of Meursing codes and their use is drawn up by Trade expert Peter Unghpakorn on his trade beta blog: https://tradebetablog.wordpress.com/2016/08/18/eu-tariff-biscuit-annex1/



Future of Meursing codes


The Meursing code is a staple of EU agrifood trade.
The UK policy however is to abandon Meursing codes as an agricultural policy, due to the fact that it is universally disliked by trade and policy (Defra) alike – the tax-raising reasons for it having come into existence in the first place are not UK policy.
However, as with much of the Northern Ireland protocol, there are additional implications for UK government and Northern Ireland traders with NI remaining in a special relationship with the EU’s Customs Union.
Initial thoughts are that the impact of the NI protocol will not be felt for GB traders, but NI traders will continue to need to apply Meursing codes to imports of specific types if the good is considered to be at risk of being further transported to the EU.
At the very least, this requires DIT policy and DDaT to retain some knowledge of the Meursing challenge, even if the majority of the UK will not be subject to the controls

Application of a Meursing code in detail – Waffles and wafers


Let’s take “waffles and wafers - with a water content exceeding 10% by weight”, commodity code 1905320500.

The third country duty reads as follows:9.00% + EA MAX 20.7% + ADFM
This is a complex compound duty involving both a ceiling and a pair of Meursing-related placeholders. These placeholders come in three forms, which, in the EU are labelled:
EA – Agricultural component 
ADFM – Additional duty on flour
ADSZ – Additional duty on sugar (not shown here, but the principle applies)
The labels are based on French and German abbreviations (élément agricole, farine / mehl; sucre / Zucker)
The next section shows the breakdown – and what traders have to do


Unpicking complex agricultural duties


The waffle duty 9.00% + EA MAX 20.7% + ADFM is made up of 4 measure components – please review the training manual on measure components for a detailed view of these.


        
          
Duty expression ID
Duty amount
Commentary


01
9.00

-
Meursing placeholder –   agricultural component

Ceiling ad valorem ( … up to a   maximum of …)

-
Meursing placeholder – additional   duty on flour


        
      

The first thing to notice is that the Meursing placeholders have no duties assigned to them – it is not possible to assign duty amounts to these measure components; they operate as placeholders that are filled in only when traders declare the content of the various delicious ingredients.
The trader goes to (for example) the gov.uk URL below, enters the component %ages and then is eventually presented with a 4-digit code, such as 7364.
Duties are then assigned specifically against the Meursing additional code 7364, totally independent of the hundreds of commodities that are subject to them – this is unique in the tariff database, where duties are usually against combinations of commodity codes and additional codes - not with Meursings.


https://www.gov.uk/additional-commodity-code
Implications for Tariffs project


Although it is theoretically possible that the UK will need to manage Meursing additional codes and their associated duties in the future, it is highly unlikely
Recommendation would be that no interface functionality is constructed to allow for managing Meursing codes themselves, as it is hugely complex.
Theoretically, if we wanted to just change the duties associated with the Meursing additional codes, this is possible: it is a matter of assigning duties direct to an additional code, rather than to a combination of commodity codes and additional codes.

Meursing table and the reduction indicator


There is one Meursing table but multiple layers of tariffs assigned against it
The “reduction indicator” is assigned to the tariff measure on the commodity code and to the duty assigned to the additional code. The border system picks the indicator that matches to select the right duty.
In use with multiple preferential agreements that reference composite agrigoods.
Japan goes to town on the usage of reduction indicators, forcing the EU to change its Taric schema to accommodate another three reduction tables.
By the end of the implementation period, be aware of two facts:
we will have done away with the concept of Meursing codes in the UK, therefore the reduction indicator will be irrelevant
we will not have a trade agreement with Japan
BUT:
we will need to honour the NI protocol, meaning Meursings will apply to imports of at risk goods from RoW and GB to NI, meaning DIT and DDaT need to continue to be aware of their presence.


Type 8, A, B, C – Anti-subsidy / anti-dumping codesA Trade Remedy is explained elsewhere, but the important thing to note is that, for the two types of trade remedy that are by some distance the most abundant, Anti-dumping duties and Anti-subsidy duties, the punitive import duties are set against specific exporting companies that are deemed to have acted unlawfully, not against entire countries.
Essentially, a company is proven to have been dumping1 its goods on an overseas market (e.g. the European Union or the United Kingdom), or to have been receiving unlawful state subsidy to undercut international competitors, and this activity is found to have been damaging businesses in those overseas nations. In such cases, the nation or bloc’s Trade Remedies body, such as our own Trade Remedies Authority, is entitled to investigate and impose punitive duties specifically against the companies that have been proven to have acted unlawfully.
In the case of Trade Remedies, the 4-digit additional code is set to represent the company from which the good is imported, or in some cases, a multitude of companies that have been found guilty of the same infraction.


By way of example:
Code C316 refers to Bengang Steel Plates Co., Ltd (Benxi, Liaoning)
Code C333 refers to all of:
* Aeolus Tyre Co., Ltd;
* Aeolus Tyre (Taiyuan) Co., Ltd;
* Qingdao Yellow Sea Rubber Co., Ltd;
* Pirelli Tyre Co., Ltd
To create a punitive trade remedy duty against a the import of “flat rolled steel” from “Bengang Steel Plates”, you assign a 552 measure against commodity code 7225990092 and additional code C316.

When the European Commission first set up the Taric database to cater for all trade eventualities, they were somewhat guilty of short-sightedness when it came to Trade Remedies.
They set up the additional type code ‘8’ in 1972 to deal with all future companies implicated in Trade Remedy cases. To be fair, this lasted until 1999, when the 1,000 possible permutations within the ‘8 ‘ type code (000 to 999) were exhausted. They then moved on to using ‘A’. In 2013, they moved on to ‘B’ and in ‘2015’ to ‘C’. By 2019, type ‘C’ was already half used up, so the expectation would be that they will move on to another additional code type within the next 2 years.
‘D’ is already used for dual use codes, albeit it is currently dormant.
In preparing for the multiple abortive stabs at EU Exit, the project team has (via scripts) created an additional set of additional code types (‘E’ and ‘F’) to cater for the inevitable expansion and deviation.
Additional codes, according to the Taric schema may be alphabetical, as well as numeric – alpha characters have never been used by the EU, but there is no reason why we could not use them in the future in the UK.


Additional codes used in Trade Remedies measures are essentially meaningless beyond Tariff – there is literally no reference against any international database of companies, nor any attempt to make the data set atomic and ‘cleansed’
You are likely to find multiple instances of the same company cropping up in the database on multiple occasions.
Be careful about the shenanigans that companies get up to evade punitive duties – most often by setting up subsidiaries in overseas nations with similar names: these are not the same company, nor the same additional code, but they may have very similar company names.

Additional codes cannot be applied universally …
There is an additional many to many table within the tariff database that determines which additional code types can be used against which measure types. Currently there are 74 permutations of additional codes against measure types: there is little surprising about the alignment – e.g. you can only assign additional codes of type 8, A, B or C to measure types that are associated with Trade Remedies.

20.title: Geographical areas
20.content:
Geographical areas


Geographical areas




Introduction to geographical areas


Identifying geographical areas


About country groups




Geographical area membership


Relationship of measures to geographical areas


Relationship of quotas to geographical areas


Key user needs – geographical area


Key business processing rules – geographical areas






Introduction to geographical areas

All measures must be assigned to a single geographical area entity.
This entity, derived from the geographical_areas view may itself be:


a single country (like Namibia)
a group of countries (like Cariforum [a Caribbean trading bloc])
a region – which is a slight misnomer, meaning as it does a country that has yet to be 
fully incorporated, like Kosovo, which remains partially recognised.

A quota though may be assigned to multiple geographical area entities. While this is the case in the EU, the UK is trying to abandon this, for example there is a wine quota (09.1530) in use for the West Balkan countries1 that is going to be split into 6 individual quotas post-implementation period.
A geographical area that is defined as being a country group will have one or more countries (or regions) designated as members of that country group.

Identifying geographical areas

An identifier for a country group (geographical_area_id) is structured depending on the type of area in question.
The geographical code field dictates what type of geographical area is involved:


0 Country
1 Country group
2 Region

For all countries and regions, the code is a 2-digit upper-case alphabetical string


For countries, this is based on the international standard (ISO_3166-1) (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_3166-1_alpha-2)
For regions, i.e. unincorporated states, the code is typically a 2-digit string beginning with X, followed by the first letter of the country. e.g. as an upshot of the splintering of the former Yugoslavia, Serbia and Kosovo were formed as ‘regions’, not countries: Serbia = XS, Kosovo = XK. Even though Serbia is now a fully recognised sovereign state, it remains a region (practical implications of flipping; Kosovo is still officially considered to be a part of Serbia by over half the world).

For country groups, the code is an alpha-numeric string of 4-digits.


For country groups set up by the EU, these 4-digit strings are always numeric, e.g. 1001 = Erga Omnes (whole world)
For nationally setup groups (historically managed by HMRC), the groups are alpha-numeric, for example F006 (Phytosanitary certificates)


About country groupsThe last example on the previous page (F006 Phytosanitary certificates) shows that the country groups do not have to align to an enshrined globally understood trading entity like EU (1011), CARIFORUM (1033) or GSP LDC (2005).
Because the meat and drink of Taric and TAP is to produce measures, which can be connected to just one single geographical area, it is often simpler just to create a group of countries and apply the measure to the group and not the individual countries.
This can often be at the expense of making total sense however. For example, to execute the regulations associated with handloomed products, a group has been set up to accommodate the countries to which a quota applies for such products – the name of the group is “Silk or cotton handloom products”.

Geographical area membershipGeographical areas that represent country groups (area code 1) are designed to include member countries
A geographical area group can only contain regions or countries (area codes 0 and 2), not other geographical area groups – any attempt to assign a country group to another country group as a member must not be permitted and cause a business rule failure at HMRC. A geographical area’s membership of a country group is bookended by a start date and potentially and end date, where absolutely required.
While geographical areas are absolutely not a volatile area within the application, and the changes are few and far between, there are a number of use cases where membership does change, albeit infrequently. For example, countries move in and out of GSP tiers from year to year as their progress or decline economically.
Steel safeguards work on country groups created specifically for the purpose of applying punitive duties against large numbers of countries; these groups tend to change from year to year, as we learn more about the impact of the punitive duties on trade flows.
The UK may choose to create country groups to apply specific regulatory controls.
Relationship of measures to geographical areas

All measures are assigned to precisely one geographical area.
That area may be a country, region (non-incorporated country) or a group of countries.
If the geographical area is a country group, then it is possible to exclude (one or more) members of that country group from the measure via inclusion in the measure_excluded_geographical_areas table.
The excluded country must be a member of that group.
Please note: both the excluded_geographical_area and geographical_area_id fields refer to the excluded country, not the group.

Relationship of quotas to geographical areas

All quotas need to be represented both as measures and within the structures related to quotas.
With licensed quotas, these are only represented by quotas.
The relationship of geographical areas to quotas needs to be reflected in both the measures and quotas structures (except for licensed quotas).
Therefore both the relationship of quotas to their origins and measures to the related geographical areas needs to be managed and synchronised in the data creation.

Key user needs – geographical area

Rule

GA1

Required

Nomenclature


Nomenclature




Managing goods classification – user needs


Key business rules






Combined Nomenclature, Harmonised System - Structure
HS - Harmonised System


The first six digits of the code numbers of the tariff or TARIC have been regulated by the World Customs Organization (WCO) in the form of the HS nomenclature world-wide since 1988.
HS is currently used in 176 countries. A revision takes place regularly, roughly every 5 years (so far, 1996, 2002, 2007, 2012, 2017). Next change anticipated in 2022.

CN - Combined Nomenclature


The “Combined Nomenclature” is published in the Official Journal of the European Community in October each year and specifies the first eight digits of the Tariff/Taric, as well as third country tariff rates for the following year. This eight-digit nomenclature can not be changed over a period of one year and applies both in the EU and the Associated States (BG, RO, TR, etc.).

TARIC - Tarif Intégré Communautaire / Tarif intégré des Communautés européennes


Taric, the tariff rate of the European Communities, is the same as the CN in the first eight digits. There is, therefore, a uniform marking for customs purposes and statistics. The Taric is subdivided however by the Taric sub-positions (from the ninth place) more deeply.
As the combined nomenclature is not sufficiently detailed to support the community tariff and commercial legislation, the 8-digit codes can be broken down into 10-digit codes called “TARIC codes”. 
These codes are created at any time, according to the legislative needs.

image
Harmonised system sections


The Harmonised System is categorised into sections and chapters
The section is a logical grouping that is not reflected in the nomenclature.
Each chapter, which is a subdivision of a section, is fully self-contained within the logical section.
Sections are represented by Roman numerals (1 to 21 / I to XXI)

      Concept definition & terminology 2


The UK refers to the full list of products in the UK Tariff as the Goods Classification – this is synonymous with the broad name for the full list of products: goods nomenclature or just nomenclature.
In the EU, this is referred to under multiple names: often the EU refers to the Tariff as the “Combined Nomenclature” (CN), though officially this refers only to the first 8 digits of the code.
Within the broader body, the individual elements referring to specific products are called commodity codes.
The commodity code is what is entered into the SAD (C88) form – the Single Administrative Document that acts as the import declaration form – see ringed box to the right.
There is a total of 24,504 commodity codes (as of 1st December 2019): of these 15,887 are declarable end-lines (see definition later).


Concept definition & terminology 2
There are three key concepts to understand in this section. All of these have a significant impact on the measures that can be defined and managed by Tariff Managers:


commodity codes
product line suffixes
indents


Commodity codes, product line suffixes and indents in practice


The schematic to the right illustrates a ‘hierarchy’ starting from the very first commodity code in the Tariff (0100 00 00 00) down to the last end-line under the 1st major HS heading branch (0101 90 00 00), i.e. Live horses, asses, mules and hinnies
This shows the commodity codes, split into segments for ease of reading, the product line suffix and the indent, as well as the current description of the commodity code.
The physical indent on the description matches the indent field.
Hence, Horses is a ‘child’ of ‘Live horses, asses, mules and hinnies’ and ‘Pure-bred breeding animals’ is a child of ‘Horses’ – however these relationships are inferred, not explicit.
You will notice that there are two zeroes at the start of the tree – this is a slightly bewildering treatment from the EU, but we need to work with it: the HS chapter and the HS heading both use an indent of 0. This will not be of huge immediate interest, as these codes will not change until the lead-up to January 2022.


If one were to try and print out the whole commodity tree (c. 24,500 lines), you would:


select the commodity codes with current validity
sort them by commodity code and then product line suffix
indent them using the indent field

Declarability and measure assignment


A SAD form requires that the trader enter the most detailed description possible for the good that is being traded, not something vague like ‘Horses’
There are two rules that define whether or not a good is declarable, i.e. whether or not it can be entered onto a SAD form:
first, a good must have a product line suffix (PLS) of “80”: anything else cannot be traded – these commodity codes are in the database purely as structural fillers
second, a good must be an end-line aka a leaf. i.e. it must not have any children.
In the example to the left, the declarable commodities are those with a      against them
Although 0101 29 00 00, 01010 00 00 00 and 0101 00 00 00 all have a PLS of “80”, they all have child codes underneath them, therefore cannot be declared.




In the example above (red marquee), it is interesting to note (and this is key in understanding where a product line suffix other than “80” is used), that there are two items with the commodity code 0101 21 00 00.
One has a PLS of 10, the other has a PLS of 80.
This is common and is likely to be a treatment we need to get used to in the UK for future change.

Jams and jellies are very complex



The image above shows the complexity of certain hierarchies.
The indent numbers have been doctored slightly to show the true number of indents, ignoring the double zero noted previously.
There are actually 14 tiers of data in certain points in the hierarchy, as shown here
This is exceptional however
Please also note the apparently inconsistent use of product line suffixes: why has 2007 99 39 00 got a PLS of “80” when it is clearly an intermediate code?
The answer seems to be that the non-80 code is used where there is a need to insert a structural heading with the same commodity code as the subsequent code, presumably due to space restrictions in the hierarchy.

Smashing preconceptions on hierarchical inheritance



This is undoubtedly an unusually complex tree, however it does illustrate well a concept that needs to be understood, to help the Tariff management team to grasp the idea of inheritance, which is critical in measure management.
The 10-digit commodity code is divided into 5 pairs of digits.
While it is alluring to consider that these two digit pairs provide enough information to work out the hierarchy, this is coincidental, though, certainly at the top of the hierarchy, frequently true.

There are five main reasons why new commodities are required
New commodities - examples

Do not underestimate WCO changes



The graph to the left shows the peaks and troughs of nomenclature management over the last 10 years
The 2 big peaks are on 1st Jan 2012 and 1st Jan 2017, the to dates in the last 10 years where the WCO has made alterations to their HS6 structures.
Every non-WCO year follows a similar peak / trough structure
Big peak in Jan (annual CN code changes, smaller peak in July (new suspension), ad hoc for the rest of the year
2019 has been an outlier, as commodity code changes have taken place throughout the year

January 2022 will require a lot of preparation

WCO 5-year changes are significant



This shows the change from 31st December to 2nd January on just a small branch 0305 59 00
Most of these changes were deletions, not creations.
The spike of 2,334 was more like 4,500 actual changes

WCO HS correlation tables



Here is a page from a 60-page correlation table document, comparing the HS systems of 2012 and 2017
The WCO specify the changes that are made to the 4 and 6 digit codes that they master.
But … the majority of the change is felt lower down the hierarchy.
You move a parent, you have to move the children.
And in moving a child, you have to give it a new commodity code, due to the need to sequence by comm code and pls.
This really means ending an old comm code and creating a new 



How will we decide on new commodity codes? How will we facilitate alignment with the EU?The answer has to be that we follow the EU’s changed precisely
There are two additional concepts that are useful to know, but play a far smaller part in the management of goods classification. Origins and successorsare intended to create an audit trail when commodity codes change

Origins
Origins


An origin defines the commodity code from which a new commodity code was derived.
When a commodity code is split into two, the ‘origin’ of the two (or more) new commodity codes is the parent commodity code.




In the example above, a successor will have been created for codes 2001 90 70 10 and 2001 90 70 90 of2001 90 70 00.
It is mandatory that at least one origin is created for every new commodity code
However, this data is of zero value to the Tariff Application

Successors


An successor defines the commodity code into which an existing commodity code has been absorbed.
It is not mandatory for a successor code to be created, though they may be created.

Residual codes


The sweet peppers example can also be used to exemplify residual codes.
A residual code is the code usually labelled ’Other’ which is created when a code is split into a specific and remainder part.
In this example 2001 90 70 00 is split into 2 child codes.


The specific code is assigned 10 as the final 2 digits.
The residual code is assigned 90 as the final 2 digits.
If in future more child codes as added to the parent as siblings to 10 and 90, then these are assigned 20, 30, 40 etc as the final 2 digits, while space remains.





If a code is split on the last digit, rather than the last 2 digits, it is usually split into 1 and 9, for example:




There are more than 6,500 residual codes in the database
